abnormal is found on physical examination. A CT scan is performed and two representative images are shown (Images 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gallstones","Carcinoma of the stomach","Gastrointestinal stromal tumour","Pancreatic neoplasm","Duodenal ulcer"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is an area of thickening in the distal stomach with an ulcer and heaped-up surrounding tissue at the level of the incisura angularis (lesser curve of the stomach) (Image 1, 2). This has all the hallmarks of malignancy. The diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarcinoma of the stomach\u003C/strong\u003E was confirmed on a subsequent endoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pancreas appears normal on these views and there is no filling defect that could suggest a gastrointestinal stromal tumour. The duodenum cannot be seen on these films and the gallbladder does not contain any stones.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cross-sectional imaging can be useful in identifying primary gastrointestinal tract lesions - but should not be considered the initial investigation in suspected cases."],"references":["Fock KM. Review article: the epidemiology and prevention of gastric cancer. Aliment Pharmacol Ther 2014; 40:250-60. Available online: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24912650/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39543"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1877"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19977"},{"type":"media","id":"19978"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19979"},{"type":"media","id":"19980"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19977"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4b2e1f1d-6fc6-4e97-911d-84421d131c99.jpg","thumbUrl":"h